The numbers are stark. Here's the full architectural analysis:

```json
{
  "executive_summary": "The system faces an imminent capacity crisis. At 20% MoM growth, disk storage hits 95% in Month 1, database CPU hits 90% in Month 2, and API servers saturate by Month 2. By Month 12, the system must handle ~446K orders/day (9x current) with a projected 3.5TB database. The plan proposes three phases: immediate query optimization and disk expansion (Months 0-1), read replica and caching introduction (Months 2-4), and data partitioning with service extraction (Months 5-9). Full table scans on order search and delivery history aggregation are the highest-ROI fixes and should start today. With a 4-engineer team, sequencing is critical — this plan front-loads the highest-impact, lowest-risk work.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "PostgreSQL Primary",
        "responsibility": "Write path for all order mutations, source of truth for transactional data",
        "boundaries": "Handles only writes and real-time point lookups after Phase 2. Sheds read traffic to replicas."
      },
      {
        "name": "PostgreSQL Read Replica(s)",
        "responsibility": "Serve all read-heavy queries: order search, reporting, delivery history aggregation",
        "boundaries": "Eventually consistent (acceptable lag <1s). No writes. Introduced in Phase 2."
      },
      {
        "name": "Application Cache Layer (Redis)",
        "responsibility": "Cache hot-path data: recent orders by customer, delivery status, frequently accessed aggregations",
        "boundaries": "TTL-based invalidation. Cache-aside pattern. Not a source of truth."
      },
      {
        "name": "API Server Fleet",
        "responsibility": "Handle HTTP requests, route reads vs writes, enforce business logic",
        "boundaries": "Stateless. Horizontally scalable. Read/write routing logic added in Phase 2."
      },
      {
        "name": "Order Search Index",
        "responsibility": "Serve customer order search without full table scans (B-tree index or dedicated search)",
        "boundaries": "Derived data. Rebuilt from primary. Covers the #1 slow query path."
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery History Materialized View / Pre-aggregation",
        "responsibility": "Serve delivery history aggregation queries from pre-computed data",
        "boundaries": "Refreshed periodically or via triggers. Covers the #2 slow query path."
      },
      {
        "name": "Partitioned Order Archive",
        "responsibility": "Store orders older than 90 days in time-partitioned tables, keeping the hot working set small",
        "boundaries": "Same schema, transparent to application via partition routing. Phase 3."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "API Server",
        "to": "PostgreSQL Primary",
        "contract": "All write operations (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE). Connection pooling via PgBouncer (max 100 connections per server).",
        "coupling_type": "tight — transactional consistency required"
      },
      {
        "from": "API Server",
        "to": "PostgreSQL Read Replica",
        "contract": "All read queries routed here after Phase 2. Stale reads acceptable (<1s lag).",
        "coupling_type": "loose — can fall back to primary if replica lags"
      },
      {
        "from": "API Server",
        "to": "Redis Cache",
        "contract": "Cache-aside: check cache → miss → query DB → populate cache. TTL 60-300s depending on data type.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — system functions without cache, just slower"
      },
      {
        "from": "PostgreSQL Primary",
        "to": "PostgreSQL Read Replica",
        "contract": "Streaming replication. Async. Monitor replication lag with alerting at >2s.",
        "coupling_type": "infrastructure coupling — managed by PostgreSQL"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "Writes: API → PgBouncer → PostgreSQL Primary → async replication → Read Replica. Reads (after Phase 2): API → Redis (cache hit?) → yes: return / no: Read Replica → populate cache → return. Order search: API → indexed query on Read Replica (B-tree on customer_id + created_at). Delivery history: API → materialized view on Read Replica. Archive queries (Phase 3): transparent partition pruning on date range.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "CQRS-lite (Read/Write Splitting)",
        "rationale": "The workload is heavily read-biased (order lookups, search, reporting). Splitting reads to replicas immediately halves primary CPU load without application rewrites. This is not full CQRS — same model, just routing."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Cache-Aside with TTL",
        "rationale": "Hot data (recent orders, delivery status) is read repeatedly. Redis cache with short TTLs provides 10-100x latency improvement on cache hits with minimal consistency risk. Simpler than write-through for a 4-person team."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Materialized Views for Aggregation",
        "rationale": "Delivery history aggregation is an expensive read query that doesn't need real-time data. Pre-computing results on a schedule (every 5-15 min) eliminates repeated full scans."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Time-Based Table Partitioning",
        "rationale": "At 3.5TB projected size, the working set must be reduced. Partitioning orders by month enables partition pruning (most queries hit recent data) and makes archival/deletion of old data a simple partition drop."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Connection Pooling (PgBouncer)",
        "rationale": "As API servers scale from 4 to 8-12 instances, direct connections exhaust PostgreSQL's max_connections. PgBouncer multiplexes connections efficiently."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Order (root: order_id, contains line items, status transitions)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Tracking",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Delivery (root: delivery_id, linked to order_id, contains status history, timestamps)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["Customer (root: customer_id, referenced by Order and Delivery)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Reporting / Analytics",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["Read-only projections — no aggregates, consumes data from Order and Delivery contexts"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Delivery Tracking",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Order context publishes order events, Delivery context subscribes"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Reporting",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Reporting reads Order data as-is, no translation layer needed yet"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery Tracking",
        "downstream": "Reporting",
        "relationship": "Conformist — same as above, reporting consumes delivery data directly"
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Read replicas instead of sharding for Phase 2",
      "gains": "Dramatically simpler to implement — no application changes for write routing, no cross-shard queries. A 4-person team can ship this in 1-2 weeks.",
      "sacrifices": "Doesn't solve write scalability. If write volume becomes the bottleneck (unlikely before Month 9 at this growth), sharding becomes necessary.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Horizontal sharding by customer_id (too complex for team size and current needs)", "Move to a distributed database like CockroachDB or Citus (operational complexity too high for 4 engineers)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Table partitioning over archival to a separate store",
      "gains": "Transparent to the application — no code changes for queries. PostgreSQL handles partition pruning automatically. Same backup/restore tooling.",
      "sacrifices": "Still one database engine. If data grows beyond what PostgreSQL can handle (unlikely within 12 months), will need a more radical change.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Archive to S3 + Athena (good for analytics but adds operational surface area)", "Separate hot/cold databases (doubles operational burden for a small team)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Redis cache-aside over application-level memoization",
      "gains": "Shared cache across all 4+ API server instances. Survives deploys. Observable (Redis metrics).",
      "sacrifices": "New infrastructure component to operate. Cache invalidation complexity.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["In-process LRU cache (doesn't share across instances, cold after deploys)", "Write-through cache (more complex, harder to reason about for team)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Index optimization before any infrastructure changes",
      "gains": "Highest ROI per engineer-hour. A missing index on customer_id likely causes the full table scan. Can be deployed in a day with zero downtime (CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY). May buy 2-3 months of breathing room.",
      "sacrifices": "Indexes consume disk space (already at 85%) and slow writes marginally. But the trade-off is overwhelmingly positive.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Skip straight to caching (masks the problem, doesn't fix it)"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Read replica count",
      "evolution_path": "Start with 1 replica, add more as read traffic grows. No application changes needed — connection pooler handles routing."
    },
    {
      "area": "Cache layer",
      "evolution_path": "Redis is optional — system works without it, just slower. Can tune TTLs, add/remove cached entities incrementally."
    },
    {
      "area": "API server fleet size",
      "evolution_path": "Stateless servers scale horizontally. Auto-scaling group can go from 4 to 12+ with load-based triggers."
    },
    {
      "area": "Partition granularity",
      "evolution_path": "Start with monthly partitions. Can switch to weekly if monthly partitions are still too large. Repartitioning is a data migration but not a schema change."
    },
    {
      "area": "Future service extraction",
      "evolution_path": "If the team grows beyond 6-8 engineers, Delivery Tracking and Reporting are natural candidates for service extraction. The read/write split and domain boundaries laid in Phases 1-2 make this easier."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "PostgreSQL as primary datastore",
      "reason": "Migrating away from PostgreSQL would be a massive effort. All optimizations in this plan double down on PostgreSQL. This is intentional — PostgreSQL can handle this scale, and the team knows it. Don't fight the database."
    },
    {
      "area": "Order table schema",
      "reason": "Partitioning and indexing strategies depend on the order table structure. Significant schema changes (e.g., splitting orders into multiple tables) would require reworking partitions and indexes."
    },
    {
      "area": "Synchronous write path",
      "reason": "This plan does not introduce async write processing (queues). If write latency becomes a problem, adding a queue is a larger architectural change."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Disk fills before index/partition work completes — at 85% utilization and Month 1 projection of 98%, the database could run out of disk space within 3-4 weeks",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "IMMEDIATE: Expand disk storage to 1TB (or enable auto-scaling storage if on cloud). This is a day-0 action. Do not wait for any other optimization."
    },
    {
      "risk": "CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY on a 400GB table under 70% CPU load could push the database into instability",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Run index creation during lowest-traffic window. Monitor replication lag and CPU. Set statement_timeout. Have a REINDEX plan if it fails partway."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Growth rate exceeds 20% MoM — if a seasonal spike or viral event pushes growth higher, timelines compress",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Build Phase 1 optimizations for 3x headroom, not 1.2x. Monitor weekly, not monthly. Have a 'break glass' plan: spin up read replicas immediately if P99 exceeds 1.5s."
    },
    {
      "risk": "4-engineer team cannot execute all three phases while also delivering features",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Phase 1 requires ~1 engineer for 1-2 weeks. Phase 2 requires 2 engineers for 3-4 weeks. Phase 3 requires 2 engineers for 4-6 weeks. Total: ~60-80 engineer-days over 9 months. This is achievable but leaves little slack. Defer Phase 3 if growth slows."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Cache stampede — when a popular cache key expires, all API servers simultaneously query the database",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Implement jittered TTLs and request coalescing (single-flight pattern). Redis supports SETNX-based locking for cache population."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Replication lag on read replica causes stale reads that confuse users (e.g., order placed but not visible)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Read-your-writes pattern: after a write, route that user's reads to primary for 5 seconds. Monitor replica lag with alerting at 2s threshold."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Three phases, strictly sequenced by urgency and ROI.\n\n**PHASE 1 — Survive (Months 0-1, 1 engineer):**\n1. DAY 0: Expand disk to 1TB+ (ops task, no code).\n2. DAY 1-3: Add missing indexes — CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY on orders(customer_id, created_at) and delivery(order_id, created_at). This alone should drop order-search-by-customer from full table scan to index scan, likely reducing P99 from 800ms to <200ms.\n3. DAY 4-7: Create materialized view for delivery history aggregation. Refresh every 15 minutes via pg_cron. Repoint the aggregation query to the materialized view.\n4. DAY 7-10: Deploy PgBouncer in front of PostgreSQL if not already present. Configure connection limits.\n5. Validate: P99 should drop below 300ms. CPU should drop to ~45-50% at peak.\n\n**PHASE 2 — Breathe (Months 2-4, 2 engineers):**\n1. Stand up PostgreSQL read replica (streaming replication).\n2. Add read/write routing in the application layer — all SELECTs go to replica, all writes go to primary.\n3. Deploy Redis. Implement cache-aside for: customer's recent orders (TTL 120s), delivery status (TTL 60s), order counts/aggregations (TTL 300s).\n4. Scale API fleet from 4 to 6 instances.\n5. Add monitoring: replica lag, cache hit rate, query latency per endpoint.\n6. Validate: Primary CPU should drop to ~30%. P99 should be <150ms.\n\n**PHASE 3 — Scale (Months 5-9, 2 engineers):**\n1. Implement table partitioning on orders by month (use PostgreSQL declarative partitioning).\n2. Migrate existing data into partitions (rolling migration, partition at a time).\n3. Scale API fleet to 8-12 instances with auto-scaling.\n4. Add a second read replica if read traffic demands it.\n5. Implement data retention policy — archive or drop partitions older than 24 months.\n6. Validate: Database handles 446K orders/day with <50% CPU on primary.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "SQL migration: CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_customer_created ON orders(customer_id, created_at)",
      "SQL migration: CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_delivery_order_created ON delivery(order_id, created_at)",
      "SQL migration: CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW delivery_history_summary AS (aggregation query)",
      "SQL migration: Schedule refresh via pg_cron — SELECT cron.schedule('refresh_delivery_summary', '*/15 * * * *', 'REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY delivery_history_summary')",
      "Application config: PgBouncer configuration (pgbouncer.ini)",
      "Application config: Redis connection configuration",
      "Application layer: Read/write connection routing middleware",
      "Application layer: Cache-aside wrapper for order queries",
      "SQL migration: Partition table definition for orders (Phase 3)",
      "Infrastructure: Read replica provisioning (Terraform/CloudFormation/manual)",
      "Monitoring: Dashboard for replica lag, cache hit rate, query latency percentiles"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "1. All index creation MUST use CONCURRENTLY to avoid locking. 2. Materialized views MUST use REFRESH CONCURRENTLY (requires a unique index on the view). 3. Cache keys should follow the pattern: {entity}:{id}:{version} with jittered TTLs. 4. Read/write routing should be at the connection/middleware level, not per-query. 5. Partitioning should use PostgreSQL 12+ declarative partitioning with a default partition for safety. 6. All schema changes should be backward-compatible and deployed independently from application changes.",
